TY  - JOUR
AU  - Abudy, Menachem Meni
AU  - Wohl, Avi
T1  - Corporate Bond Trading on a Limit Order Book Exchange*
PY  - 2018
Y1  - 2018/07/01
DO  - 10.1093/rof/rfx054
JO  - Review of Finance
JA  - Rev Financ
VL  - 22
IS  - 4
SP  - 1413
EP  - 1440
SN  - 1572-3097
AB  - We investigate the trading of corporate bonds (c-bonds) by an open limit order book (LOB) mechanism. To do so, we use the case of the Tel Aviv Stock Exchange (TASE) as a laboratory, in which both stocks and c-bonds are traded by an LOB mechanism. Contrary to the OTC market in the USA, the TASE c-bond market is liquid with narrow spreads and low price dispersion. The short-term traders (STT), who are the analog of the market makers in the LOB, have small trading rents and unconcentrated activity (a low Herfindahl index). In the cross-section of bonds, the low concentration is related to low spreads, low price dispersion, and small STT rents. The non-STT [including retail investors (RIs), whose participation is significant] competes with the STT on quotation and tends to tighter quotes. RIs’ activity contributes to narrower spreads.
Y2  - 3/26/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/rof/rfx054
ER  - 



